{"name": "surf-archiver", "metadata": {"name": "surf-archiver", "version": "0.1.1a4", "classifiers": ["Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.10", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.11", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.12", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.13", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.9"], "home_page": null, "license": null, "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["aio-pika", "pydantic", "s3fs", "typer"], "summary": null, "upload_time": 1734604624}, "documentation": ["# surf-archiver\n\nThe `surf-archiver` tool consists of two components: \n1) a CLI tool\n2) a remote client which can execute CLI installed on a remote machine\n\nThe CLI tool copies daily data from S3 supported storage, bundling it into a per \nexperiment per day tar archives. Once completed it emits a message via RabbitMQ. The \nintended use case is for the CLI tool to installed on the Surf Data Archive and remotely \ntriggered daily.\n\n\nThe tool copies data based on the S3 key. It is assumed that the keys have the following\nstructure:\n```\n<SRC BUCKET>/<images|videos>/<EXPERIMENT-ID>/YYYYMMDD/*.tar\n```\n\nThe resulting archive will be created at:\n```\n<DATA DIR>/<images|videos>/<EXPERIMENT-ID>/YYYY-MM-DD.tar\n```\n\n# Installation of the CLI tool\n\nThe CLI tool can be installed via [pipx](https://github.com/pypa/pipx).\n\n\nIn order to run the tool needs some configuration. It can be configured by via a yaml \nfile:\n\n```yaml\nbucket:             # S3 bucket data is pulled from\ntarget_dir:         # Target directory data is stored in       \nconnction_url:      # RabbitMQ connection url\nexchange_name:      # RabbitMQ Exchange name\nlog_file:           # log file path\n```\n\nBy default the tool will look for this configuration in the `${HOME}/.surf-archiver`.\nThe tool will additionally look for these parameters in the shell environment. If they\nare defined here, they need to be prefixed by `surf_archiver_`. \n\n\nIn addition to the above, the following environment variables need to be set in order to\nconnect to S3.\n```bash\nAWS_SECRET_KEY_ID=\nAWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=\nAWS_ENDPOINT_URL=\n```\n\n"], "modules": [{"name": "surf_archiver.remote.main", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "surf_archiver.remote.main.main", "asynchronous": true, "params": [], "returns": null, "documentation": []}], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "surf_archiver.remote", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": [{"name": "surf_archiver.remote.WorkerSettings", "xref": {"fqname": "surf_archiver.remote.worker.WorkerSettings", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "surf_archiver.utils", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [{"name": "surf_archiver.utils.DateT", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "surf_archiver.remote.worker", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "surf_archiver.remote.worker.startup", "asynchronous": true, "params": [{"name": "ctx", "type": {"name": "dict", "xref": {"fqname": "functions.dict", "project": "--std--"}, "params": null}, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}], "variables": [{"name": "surf_archiver.remote.worker.LOGGER", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [{"name": "surf_archiver.remote.worker.Settings", "bases": ["BaseSettings"], "methods": [], "class_variables": [{"name": "surf_archiver.remote.worker.Settings.USERNAME", "type": {"name": "str", "xref": {"fqname": "functions.str", "project": "--std--"}, "params": null}, "documentation": []}, {"name": "surf_archiver.remote.worker.Settings.PASSWORD", "type": {"name": "str", "xref": {"fqname": "functions.str", "project": "--std--"}, "params": null}, "documentation": []}, {"name": "surf_archiver.remote.worker.Settings.HOST", "type": {"name": "str", "xref": {"fqname": "functions.str", "project": "--std--"}, "params": null}, "documentation": []}, {"name": "surf_archiver.remote.worker.Setting